Assignment 6¶

In this assignment, you'll analyze a collection of data sets from the San Francisco Open Data Portal and Zillow. The data sets have been stored in the SQLite database sf_data.sqlite, which you can download here. The database contains the following tables:

Table Description
crime Crime reports dating back to 2010.
mobile_food_locations List of all locations where mobile food vendors sell.
mobile_food_permits List of all mobile food vendor permits. More details here.
mobile_food_schedule Schedules for mobile food vendors.
noise Noise complaints dating back to August 2015.
parking List of all parking lots.
parks List of all parks.
schools List of all schools.
zillow Zillow rent and housing statistics dating back to 1996. More details here.

The mobile_food_ tables are explicitly connected through the locationid and permit columns. The other tables are not connected, but you may be able to connect them using dates, latitude/longitude, or postal codes.

Shapefiles for US postal codes are available here. These may be useful for converting latitude/longitude to postal codes.

Shapefiles for San Francisco Neighborhoods are available here.

By look through the three mobile food tables, one applicant only has one permit. Therefore, one method is that we can just look at mobile food schedule table, and find out which permit corresponding to the most locationid. Then, we use that permit number to find out which mobile food vendor sells at the most locations.

The second method is combine all the three three mobilefood tables, and directly find out which mobile food vendor sells at the most location.

Method 1¶

Since one applicant only has one permit, we can just look at mobile_food_schedule table, and find out which permit corresponding to the most locationid. Then, we use that permit number to find out which mobile food vendor sells at the most locations.

Method 2¶

Different method to find the mobile food vendor by combining all the three mobile food tables.

In [413]:
# combine unique mobile_food_schedule table and mobile_food_locations join by locationid
db.execute(
    "CREATE TABLE mobile_df AS SELECT DISTINCT L.*, R.* "
    "FROM (SELECT DISTINCT locationid, permit FROM mobile_food_schedule) AS L INNER JOIN mobile_food_locations AS R ON L.locationid = R.locationid"
)

You should try to come up with some questions on your own, but these are examples of reasonable questions:

  • Which parts of the city are the most and least expensive?
  • Which parts of the city are the most dangerous (and at what times)?
  • Are noise complaints and mobile food vendors related?
  • What are the best times and places to find food trucks?
  • Is there a relationship between housing prices and any of the other tables?

Please make sure to clearly state each of your questions in your submission.

For this question, I am trying to figure out which part of the San Francisco are the most and least expensive. In the Zillow table, there are many variables. I choose Median Sold Price Per Sqft as the price variables, and group price label by zip code. If we look at the price variables, we can see that there is a region 94104 has the most expensive houses in SF. Its price is over 1000 dollars per square. I mark this dot as red biggest dot in the map. I also mark the dots to be blue if the houses’ prices are between 1000 and 600, mark the dots to be green if the houses’ price are between 450 and 600, and mark dots to be black if houses’ price less than 450. Since in the Zillow table, we only have its zip code. In order to draw base map, we need longitude and latitude, so I use package ‘zipcode’ to get longitude and latitude of every region.

If we look at the map, we can see that the biggest red dot includes houses in Union Square and Financial District. This is the central business center of San Francisco, so it is reasonable to have the most expensive house prices. It also makes sense that there are one black dot and one green dot near the biggest red dot, since this two smaller dot represent the house price in Chinatown. The price of houses in Chinatown is usually lower than the average.

We can also see the smallest black dot is in region. This is the east-south corner of San Francisco. Since it is far away from the city center and do not have any tourist interests, it is reasonable to be the least expensive houses.

                GROUP BY Lat, Lon
                ORDER BY CaseNum DESC"""

                FROM crime
                WHERE Descript LIKE '%rape%' OR '%sexual%'
                GROUP BY Lat, Lon
                ORDER BY CaseNum DESC"""
rape = pd.read_sql(test_query2,db)

In the crime table, there are lots of different type of crime issues. I choose to look at drug issue and rape issue specifically because I think these two crime issues may have some relationship: increasing drug cases may increase the number of rape crimes. I count the crime number per region, and plot them in base map. The map on the left with red dot is the distribution of drug issue in SF, and the map on the right with green dot is the distribution of rape crime in SF. We can see that both two plots have the high frequency in South of Market area. This area is not very far away from the city center. Since the two plot have very similar distribution of crime happening, it is reasonable to make an assumption that increasing drug case will lead to increasing sexual assault. If we look at the rape crime distribution plot more carefully, we can see that there is another big green dot near Mission Dolores Park. So this area also has a high probability of rape crime happen.

In this part, I am trying find the best time for finding food truck. I look at the mobile_food_schedule table, and divide the table into two parts: weekdays and weekends. I count the total number of applicants/permits for every 24 hours. The first bar plot shows the distribution of time schedule of food truck in weekdays. We can see that 9 a.m. to 12 p.m have the most food trucks. This make sense, since lots of employers start work at 9, and have lunch break around 12. These food trucks can provide employers with breakfast and lunch. The second bar plot shows the distribution of time schedule of food truck during weekend. Different from the weekday plot, the distribution of food truck skewed to the right. 10 a.m to 1 p.m. have the most food truck, and even in the afternoon, from 1 p.m. to 8p.m., there are still moderate many food trucks. Because this is during the weekends, most of people tend to wake up late and sleep late. So there will be more food truck in the afternoon during the weekend compared with the weekday.

In this part, I am going to look at the park table，and want to know which kind of park appear the most in SF city, and which type of park has the most acerage. I have draw two pie charts: The first pie charts are the total acres of different type of parks in SF. we can see that regional park almost take the 71% of the total acerage. Because a regional park is an area of land preserved on account of its natural beauty, historic interest, recreational use or other reason, and under the administration of a form of local government, it make sense SF has lots of the acreage of regional parks.The Neighborhood Park or Playground also takes about 14% of the total acerage because it has total 131 locations in SF. Since SF is a very big city, it should has lots of communities and apartments, so it is reasonable to have many Neighborhood Park or Playground. Neighborhood Park or Playground is the most usual park type in sf.

The second pie charts are the mean of acreage of different type of parks in SF. We can see that Family Camp takes about half of the total acerages, and SF only has this big Family Camp. Besides Family Camp, Regional Park and Zoological Garden also has big percentage of the total acres.
